# Keyboard Events âŒ¨ï¸

- `onkeydown`: The user pushes a keyboard key.
- `onkeyup`: The user releases a key.
- `onkeypress`: The user presses a key (deprecated in modern standards, use keydown).

```javascript
// Log key pressed
document.addEventListener('keydown', function(event) {
    console.log(`Key pressed: ${event.key}`);
});
```

# addEventListener ğŸ‘‚

The `addEventListener()` method attaches an event handler to an element without overwriting existing event handlers.

Syntax: `element.addEventListener(event, function, useCapture);`

```javascript
document.getElementById("myBtn").addEventListener("click", function() {
  alert("Hello World!");
});
```

> ğŸ’¡ **Best Practice:** Use this method instead of inline attributes (e.g., `onclick`). It separates JS from HTML.

# The Event Object ğŸ“¦

When an event occurs, the browser creates an **Event object**, puts details into it, and passes it as an argument to the handler.

```javascript
button.addEventListener("click", function(event) {
  console.log(event.target); // The clicked element
  console.log(event.type);   // "click"
});
```

# preventDefault() âœ‹

Prevents the default action of the element.

Example: Prevent a link from opening the URL or a form from submitting.

```javascript
document.getElementById("myAnchor").addEventListener("click", function(event){
  event.preventDefault();
});
```
